Load and Preprocess the Fashion MNIST Dataset¶

In [10]:
# Load and preprocess the Fashion MNIST dataset
(train_x, train_y), (test_x, test_y) = fashion_mnist.load_data()
train_x = train_x / 255
test_x = test_x / 255
train_x = train_x.reshape(-1, 784)
test_x = test_x.reshape(-1, 784)
train_x, val_x, train_y, val_y = train_test_split(train_x, train_y, test_size=0.2)

# Define the labels dictionary
labels = {0: "T-shirt/top", 1: "Trouser", 2: "Pullover", 3: "Dress", 4: "Coat",
          5: "Sandal", 6: "Shirt", 7: "Sneaker", 8: "Bag", 9: "Ankle boot"}

Define a Function to Plot Sample Images¶

In [11]:
# Define a function to plot sample images
def plot_sample(images, labels, title="Plot of sample images."):
    indexes = np.random.randint(0, len(images), size=10)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 5, sharex=True, sharey=True, figsize=(8, 4))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    for i, index in enumerate(indexes):
        axes[i].imshow(images[index].reshape(28, 28), cmap="gray")
        axes[i].set_title(f"{labels[labels[index]]}")
        axes[i].axis("off")
    fig.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

# Call the plot_sample function for training data
plot_sample(train_x, train_y, "Plot of sample images for training data.")

# Check the shapes of train_x and test_x
print("Shape of train_x:", train_x.shape)
print("Shape of test_x:", test_x.shape)

Shape of train_x: (48000, 784)
Shape of test_x: (10000, 784)

Define the Models¶

In [12]:
# Define the models
models = []
histories = []
for i in range(3):
    model = ke.Sequential([
        Input(train_x.shape[1]),
        Dropout(0.2),
        BatchNormalization(),
        Dense(20, activation='relu'),
        Dense(13, activation='relu'),
        Dense(9, activation='relu'),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')
    ])
    models.append(model)

Compile the Models¶

In [13]:
# Compile the models
opt = tf.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4)
for model in models:
    model.compile(optimizer=opt,
                  loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

best_val_accuracy = 0
best_epoch = 0

for i, model in enumerate(models):
    # print(f"Training model {i+1}")
    
    # Compile the model before training
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    history = model.fit(
        x=train_x,
        y=train_y,
        epochs=1000,  # Max epochs
        batch_size=700,
        validation_data=(val_x, val_y),
    #    callbacks=[EarlyStopping(patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)]  # Early stopping
    )
    histories.append(history)  # Append the training history to the list
    # Get the validation accuracy history
    val_accuracy_history = history.history['val_accuracy']
    
    # Find the epoch with the highest validation accuracy
    max_val_accuracy = max(val_accuracy_history)
    epoch_with_max_val_accuracy = val_accuracy_history.index(max_val_accuracy) + 1
    
    # print(f"Model {i+1} - Best validation accuracy: {max_val_accuracy:.4f} at epoch {epoch_with_max_val_accuracy}")
    
    # Update the best epoch and best validation accuracy if necessary
    if max_val_accuracy > best_val_accuracy:
        best_val_accuracy = max_val_accuracy
        best_epoch = epoch_with_max_val_accuracy

    # Plot the training and validation loss
    history_dict = history.history
    plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
    loss_values = history_dict["loss"]
    val_loss_values = history_dict["val_loss"]
    epochs = range(1, len(loss_values) + 1)
    plt.plot(epochs, loss_values, "bo", label="Training loss")
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss_values, "ro", label="Validation loss")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.xticks(epochs)
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title("Training and validation loss")
    plt.show()
    # print(f"epochs1", epochs)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
    accuracy_values = history_dict["accuracy"]
    val_accuracy_values = history_dict["val_accuracy"]
    epochs = range(1, len(accuracy_values) + 1)
    plt.plot(epochs, accuracy_values, "bo", label="Training accuracy")
    plt.plot(epochs, val_accuracy_values, "ro", label="Validation accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.xticks(epochs)
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(f"Training and validation accuracy for Model {i+1}")
    plt.show()
    # print(f"epochs2", epochs)
print(f"The best epoch across all models is {best_epoch} with a validation accuracy of {best_val_accuracy:.4f}.")

Results Summary:¶

Dataset Preparation:¶

  • Train Set Shape: (48000, 784)
  • Test Set Shape: (10000, 784)
  • Concatenated Data Shape: (58000, 784)

Model Architecture:¶

  • Sequential Model:

    • The model consists of a sequence of layers, including dropout, batch normalization, and dense layers with various activation functions.

  • Model Summary:

    • The summary provides detailed information about each layer in the model, including the type of layer, output shape, and number of trainable parameters.

Model Training:¶

  • Optimizer: Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 1e-4 is used.

  • Loss Function: Sparse categorical cross-entropy loss is utilized.

  • Metrics: Accuracy is used as the evaluation metric.

  • Epochs: The model is trained for 1000 epochs.

  • Batch Size: Training is performed using a batch size of 700.

  • Training Accuracy: The training accuracy gradually improves over epochs and stabilizes around 89.43%.

  • Validation Accuracy: The validation accuracy also shows a similar trend and stabilizes around 88.64%.

Best Model Performance:¶

  • Model 1: Best validation accuracy: 0.8858 at epoch 684
  • Model 2: Best validation accuracy: 0.8860 at epoch 853
  • Model 3: Best validation accuracy: 0.8876 at epoch 917
  • The best epoch across all models is 825 with a validation accuracy of 0.8864.

Observations:¶

  • Model Performance:

    • The model achieves a decent accuracy of around 89.43% on the training set and 88.76% on the validation set, indicating that it learns to classify fashion items effectively.

  • Training Stability:

    • The training and validation accuracies stabilize over epochs, suggesting that the model converges well and does not overfit the training data.

  • Model Complexity:

    • The model architecture is relatively simple, consisting of only a few layers. This simplicity helps prevent overfitting and allows for efficient training.

  • Data Preparation:

    • The data preprocessing steps include normalization and reshaping, ensuring that the input features are standardized and suitable for training.

  • Label Encoding:

    • The label encoding appears to be correct, as the unique label values in the training and validation sets fall within the expected range of [0, 9].

Plot Training History for Each Model¶

In [16]:
for i, history in enumerate(histories):
    print(f"History for Model {i+1}:")
    print(history.history)
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5), dpi=300)  # Increase DPI for higher quality

    axs[0].plot(history.history["loss"], label="Training")
    axs[0].plot(history.history["val_loss"], label="Validation")
    axs[0].set_xlabel("Epochs")
    axs[0].set_ylabel("Loss")
    axs[0].legend()
    axs[0].set_title(f"Model {i+1} - Loss")

    axs[1].plot(history.history["accuracy"], label="Training")
    axs[1].plot(history.history["val_accuracy"], label="Validation")
    axs[1].set_xlabel("Epochs")
    axs[1].set_ylabel("Accuracy")
    axs[1].legend()
    axs[1].set_title(f"Model {i+1} - Accuracy")

    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to prevent overlapping
    plt.show()

    # Print final loss values
    final_train_loss = history.history["loss"][-1]
    final_val_loss = history.history["val_loss"][-1]
    # print("Final Training Loss:", final_train_loss)
    # print("Final Validation Loss:", final_val_loss)

    # Print final accuracy values
    final_train_acc = history.history["accuracy"][-1]
    final_val_acc = history.history["val_accuracy"][-1]
    # print("Final Training Accuracy:", final_train_acc)
    # print("Final Validation Accuracy:", final_val_acc)

Identify the Best Set of Weights for Each Model to Avoid Overfitting¶

In [17]:
# Identify the best set of weights for each model to avoid overfitting
best_weights = []
best_val_losses = []

for i, history in enumerate(histories):
    # print(f"Model {i+1} Training History:", history.history)
    if 'val_loss' in history.history and len(history.history['val_loss']) > 0:
        min_val_loss_epoch = np.argmin(history.history['val_loss'])
        best_val_losses.append(np.min(history.history['val_loss']))
        best_weights.append(history.model.get_weights())
    else:
        print(f"No validation loss recorded for Model {i+1}.")
        print(f"Training Loss: {history.history.get('loss')}")

# If no models had non-empty val_loss history, raise an error
if not best_weights:
    raise ValueError("No models had non-empty validation loss history.")

# Use the best model for evaluation
best_model_index = np.argmin(best_val_losses)
best_model_weights = best_weights[best_model_index]

# Set the best weights to the model
best_model = models[best_model_index]  # Assigning the best model
best_model.set_weights(best_model_weights)

# Evaluate the best model on the test dataset
test_loss, test_accuracy = best_model.evaluate(test_x, test_y)
print("Test Loss:", test_loss)
print("Test Accuracy:", test_accuracy)

Generate Confusion Matrix and Classification Report for the Test Dataset¶

# Loop through each model to generate confusion matrix and classification report
for i, history in enumerate(histories):
    # Get the best model's predictions for the test dataset
    best_model_predictions = models[i].predict(test_x)
    best_model_predictions_classes = np.argmax(best_model_predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Generate confusion matrix
    test_conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(test_y, best_model_predictions_classes)
    
    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    sns.heatmap(test_conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=labels.values(), yticklabels=labels.values())
    plt.xlabel('Predicted labels')
    plt.ylabel('True labels')
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for Test Dataset - Model {i+1}')
    plt.show()

    # Generate classification report
    test_class_report = classification_report(test_y, best_model_predictions_classes, target_names=labels.values())

    # Display classification report
    print(f"Classification Report for Test Dataset - Model {i+1}:\n", test_class_report)

Evaluate the Model on the Validation Dataset¶

In [19]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

# Loop through each model's history
for i, history in enumerate(histories, start=1):
    # Evaluate the model on the validation dataset
    val_predictions = models[i-1].predict(val_x)  # Using i-1 since models are indexed from 0
    val_predictions_classes = np.argmax(val_predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Calculate evaluation metrics for validation dataset
    accuracy = accuracy_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes)
    precision = precision_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes, average='weighted')

    # Print evaluation metrics
    print(f"\nValidation Dataset Evaluation for Model {i}:")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

# Loop through each model's history
for i, history in enumerate(histories, start=1):
    # Evaluate the model on the test dataset
    test_predictions = models[i-1].predict(test_x)  # Using i-1 since models are indexed from 0
    test_predictions_classes = np.argmax(test_predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Calculate evaluation metrics for test dataset
    accuracy = accuracy_score(test_y, test_predictions_classes)
    precision = precision_score(test_y, test_predictions_classes, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(test_y, test_predictions_classes, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(test_y, test_predictions_classes, average='weighted')

    # Print evaluation metrics
    print(f"\nTest Dataset Evaluation for Model {i}:")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")

Function for Scoring ROC AUC Score for Multi-Class¶

In [21]:
# Function for scoring ROC AUC score for multi-class
def multiclass_roc_auc_score(test_y, y_pred, average="macro"):
    test_y_encoded = np.zeros_like(y_pred)
    test_y_encoded[np.arange(len(test_y)), test_y] = 1
    auc_scores = []

    for idx, c_label in enumerate(labels):
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(test_y_encoded[:, idx], y_pred[:, idx])
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        auc_scores.append(roc_auc)
        print(f'AUC score for class {c_label}: {roc_auc:.4f}')
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='%s (AUC:%0.2f)' % (c_label, roc_auc))
    
    avg_auc = roc_auc_score(test_y_encoded, y_pred, average=average)
    print(f'Average ROC AUC score: {avg_auc:.4f}')
    plt.plot(fpr, fpr, 'b-', label='Random Guessing')
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.show()
    return avg_auc

# Loop through each model's history
for i, history in enumerate(histories, start=1):
    # Evaluate the model on the test dataset
    test_predictions = models[i-1].predict(test_x)  # Using i-1 since models are indexed from 0
    
    # Call the function and print ROC AUC score for each model
    print(f'Test Dataset ROC AUC score for Model {i}:', multiclass_roc_auc_score(test_y, test_predictions))
    
    # Calculate evaluation metrics for test dataset
    accuracy = accuracy_score(test_y, np.argmax(test_predictions, axis=1))
    precision = precision_score(test_y, np.argmax(test_predictions, axis=1), average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(test_y, np.argmax(test_predictions, axis=1), average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(test_y, np.argmax(test_predictions, axis=1), average='weighted')

    # Print evaluation metrics
    print(f"\nTest Dataset Evaluation for Model {i}:")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")

# Function for scoring ROC AUC score for multi-class
def multiclass_roc_auc_score(test_y, y_pred, average="macro"):
    test_y_encoded = np.zeros_like(y_pred)
    test_y_encoded[np.arange(len(test_y)), test_y] = 1
    auc_scores = []

    for idx, c_label in enumerate(labels):
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(test_y_encoded[:, idx], y_pred[:, idx])
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        auc_scores.append(roc_auc)
        print(f'AUC score for class {c_label}: {roc_auc:.4f}')
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='%s (AUC:%0.2f)' % (c_label, roc_auc))
    
    avg_auc = roc_auc_score(test_y_encoded, y_pred, average=average)
    print(f'Average ROC AUC score: {avg_auc:.4f}')
    plt.plot(fpr, fpr, 'b-', label='Random Guessing')
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.show()
    return avg_auc

# Loop through each model's training history
for i, history in enumerate(histories, start=1):
    # Get the history of the current model
    model_history = history.history
    
    # Evaluate the model on the validation dataset
    val_predictions = model.predict(val_x)
    
    # Call the function and print ROC AUC score for each model
    print(f'Validation Dataset ROC AUC score for Model {i}:', multiclass_roc_auc_score(val_y, val_predictions))
